        "content": "<p>I'm trying to show that <code>n / (n + 1)</code> converges to <code>1</code> as <code>n</code> tends to infinity. The theorem is set up as such</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">noncomputable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a₂</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">/</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Filter</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Tendsto</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a₂</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Filter</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">atTop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">nhds</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I've solved it already by converting it to the <code>ε</code> definition, but I now want to try it using filters. My plan is to convert the function to <code>1 / (1 + n⁻¹)</code> and use <code>Filter.Tendsto.div'</code> to split it into two easy limits. The problem is that when <code>n = 0</code>, these two expressions of the function aren't equal. This shouldn't matter since for all natural numbers greater than 0, this does work, but I lack the experience with filters to know how to deal with this. What should I do?</p>",
